                        <h2 class="card-title mt-3">JUSTIN FORNAL, Cultural Explorer</h2>
                        <p>
                            Justin Fornal is good at a lot of things. But describing what he does for a living is not
                            one of them—on any given expedition, he’s a cultural detective, extreme athlete, a culinary
                            explorer, or, most impressively, all of the above. But above all else, the Bronx dweller is
                            a seeker in search of the weird and wild, of the truth, and of his own personal limits.
                            Fornal has traveled 1,200 miles deep into the East African bush to learn more about the
                            Buganda tribe; he swam 100 miles around a Scottish island to create one of the rarest
                            whiskies in the world.
                            “All my stories are obsessions,” he says. “And when I can combine athleticism with cultural
                            research in the field to create something, that’s what makes it all worth it for me.”
                            Perhaps Fornal’s legacy will be as a pioneer in journalism, a sort of Hunter Thompson of the
                            Vice era. Indeed, his explorations carry as much weight and danger as any war reporter’s.
                            Later this year, he heads to Iraq to work with religious minorities; after that, he heads to
                            Afghanistan to gather a rare rock from the oldest mine and deliver it to artists in New
                            York. He’s also planning to swim 230 miles from Mopti to Timbuktu to build a clinic and
                            raise awareness in the fight against female genital mutilation. “At the heart of all my
                            field research is giving people a microphone,” he says. “I want to get the stories out there
                            while the stories can still be recorded.”
                        </p>
