                        <h2 class="card-title mt-3"> IAN WALSH, Big Wave Surfer</h2>
                        <p>
                            Say what you will about surfers, there’s nothing laid back about Ian Walsh’s approach to
                            riding waves. It makes sense given the fact that he is one of the few humans on the planet
                            chasing the biggest storms around the world and regularly charging into 50-foot barrels.
                            Walsh is leading a new breed if big wave surfer that understands that being truly prepared
                            to take on record-breaking swell when it arrives is the future of the sport. “My training is
                            entirely connected to what happens in the water,” he explains. “The time I put in at the
                            gym, on the bike, the torturous hours doing breath-hold exercises—I’m putting myself in a
                            position to ride a wave I’ve been visualizing.”
                            Walsh surfed Jaws for the first time at age 16. Three years later, he was runner-up in the
                            Billabong XXL awards for riding a 68-footer at the same break. Since then, Walsh has placed
                            in the top three of so many Big Wave events that he is on his way to cementing his spot
                            alongside Shane Dorian and Greg Noll as one of the all-time greats. But the thing he learned
                            right from an early age is that truly giant surf is rare—often occurring less a few times a
                            year—and every wave deserves absolute focus. Thus, Walsh is basically changing surfing every
                            single time he paddles out or gets towed into a wall of water. “On each big day, the level
                            of our sport progresses—the types of lines people are riding, the equipment…” he told Men’s
                            Journal. “The stakes are very high and, while you can’t control everything, you can control
                            how ready you are.”
                        </p>
