                        <p>
                            British Polar explorer Felicity Aston thinks everyone needs to really freeze their asses off
                            at least once in their life. As one of the most experienced and accomplished living Polar
                            explorers, her career has long been driven by curiosity and conservation. But these days,
                            she’s using her skills to shatter some long-standing barriers by exposing more people to the
                            Polar regions. “I wish I could take everybody to these places,” she says. “When you
                            experience them for yourself, then you care about them.” Specifically, Aston has chosen to
                            invite expedition members that challenge the idea of what an explorer looks like,
                            specializing in all-female expeditions; she recently led a team of European and Middle
                            Eastern women to the North Pole.
                            Aston began her career as a meteorologist stationed in Antarctica but decided it was time to
                            step out of her comfort zone in 2006 when she joined the first all-female British expedition
                            across the Greenland ice sheet. Six years and several polar trips later, Aston became the
                            first person ever to ski alone across Antarctica, under their own steam (which earned her
                            prestigious MBE status from the British government). It doesn’t seem swanky awards are
                            slowing her down. “Three weeks ago, the helicopter dropped us off on the ice and it was
                            -38C,” she told us after returning from the North Pole. By the end of that day, I had a girl
                            with such severe frostbite she had to leave the expedition.”
