                        <h2 class="card-title mt-3"> RUE MAPP, Activist</h2>
                        <p>
                            Rue Mapp (above, center) believes the outdoors is a place where we can leave the burdens of
                            societal dysfunction behind. Through Outdoor Afro, a nationwide network of black
                            enthusiasts, she’s helping adventurers of color connect in what’s perceived as an
                            overwhelmingly white dominion.
                            “I was going to the traditional outdoor clubs and groups, reading outdoor magazines, and I
                            wasn’t seeing myself,” she told Men’s Journal. “I was tired of being the only one—the only
                            black person on a ride, on a hike—so we put the word out. We started hearing from the other
                            ‘only ones’, and then put all the only ones together and became a community.”
                            Since founding the community in 2009, Mapp has been to the White House, was named one of the
                            most influential African Americans in the country by The Root, and received the Outdoor
                            Industry Inspiration Award. But Mapp’s work has never been more important than right now—she
                            says the outdoors is much more than an exciting escape; it’s a rare safe-haven at a time of
                            heightened insecurity. “After Ferguson, we started doing healing hikes—we took it to
                            nature,” she says. “The trees don’t know you’re black. The birds don’t know how much money
                            you have in your bank account.”
                        </p>
