                        <h2 class="card-title mt-3">STEVE AND CHRIS BOYES, Conservationists</h2>
                        <p>
                            South African conservationists Steve and Chris Boyes (in the foreground) may have different
                            skill sets, but they certainly have a very singular vision: uncover the striking beauty of
                            totally untouched landscapes—no matter what the danger—in order to save them. And in places
                            like Botswana, Rwanda, and Zambia, a simple walk in the woods can be deadly. “If you don’t
                            experience the heart of a place, you can’t represent it honestly and raise millions of
                            dollars for it—we have to know the soul of it,” says Dr. Steve Boyes, 39, who spends a lot
                            of his time lobbying in Washington or Europe, raising money, and raising awareness. “We need
                            to be able to tell a government official we’ve seen every inch of a river, so we risk our
                            lives for that once-in-a-lifetime benefit.” Steve’s brother Chris, who is two years younger,
                            is largely in charge of expedition logistics, spending up to nine months of every year out
                            in the field.
                            Known early on as “The Bush Boyes” through their work with National Geographic, and the Wild
                            Bird Trust, the two just premiered their documentary Into the Okavango at the 2018 Tribeca
                            Film Festival. It’s their most important work to date, in their effort to gather stunning
                            film footage as a way of recording a place exactly as it exists at that moment in time, for
                            generations to come. It also highlights the dangers of their work.
                            “In the film, a hippo capsizes my boat,” says Steve. “But that happens once a week.
                            Crocodiles also bump us or jump over the boat. On the river you have to be absolutely
                            focused—every hump or ripple in the water, every eddy, every movement, every sound. If you
                            drop that focus, you get in trouble.”
                        </p>
