                        <h2 class="card-title mt-3">KIT DESLAURIERS, Ski Mountaineer</h2>
                        <p>
                            You know someone is passionate about skiing when they ascend mountains that even climbers
                            are scared of just for the downhill. Kit DesLauriers has made a career of making fresh
                            tracks in some of the most technical and dangerous peaks in the world. Skiing has always
                            been in DesLauriers’ blood, as she did longs stints as a ski bum in the Alps and Rockies,
                            eventually winning back-to-back World Freeskiing Championships in 2004 and 2005. She also
                            racked up notable descents off Mt. Aspiring in New Zealand and The Grand Teton in Wyoming.
                            But she became the official queen of first descents when she became the first person ever to
                            ski the Seven Summits, the highest peak on each continent, in 2006.
                            Since then, her love of skiing remote and technical lines has evolved into a sort of extreme
                            eco-activism. DesLauriers has just set off on her third expedition to the Arctic Refuge in
                            Alaska, where she has her eyes on skiing the second highest peak in the Brook’s Range (she
                            has already skied the first, third, fourth, and fifth highest peaks—and all have been first
                            descents). But at age 49, it’s clear her priorities have shifted, slightly.
                            “Yeah, there will be a few ski descents,” she told Men’s Journal before she left. “But these
                            are adventures where I’m able to incorporate my skills into the effort to protect sacred
                            lands.” Meanwhile, DesLauriers points to a new set concerns, such as the remoteness and
                            polar bears, that come with the new style of adventure. Part of her prep for her upcoming
                            trip was handgun training.
                            One thing is clear, no matter what DesLauriers does, it will always involve skis and a
                            little downhill. “I learned early on that when I don’t have my skis, it just feels like
                            something’s missing,” she says.
