                        <h2 class="card-title mt-3">MELISSA ARNOT, Mountain Guide, Everest Record Holder</h2>
                        <p>
                            Melissa Arnot is famous throughout the adventure world for having been to the summit of
                            Everest six times, more than any other western woman. But her true legacy lies in the number
                            of times she’s been to the summit of the much more modest Mt Rainier in Washington state. As
                            one of the hardest working mountain guides in the world, Arnot has ascended Rainier over 90
                            times, delivering newbies of all ages to the summit.
                            “My greatest passion is with guiding,” she says. “First ascents are fun, but I only do
                            harder personal trips so I can empathize with clients better. I like watching people become
                            better people in the mountains.”
                            That’s not to say Arnot’s Everest climbs are a mere afterthought. She not only summited for
                            the first time at just 24 years old, but on her last Everest climb in 2016, she became the
                            first American woman to climb the mountain without supplemental oxygen. The mountain holds a
                            particularly special place in Arnot’s heart, as she believes that western guides and
                            climbers have an important opportunity to become better stewards in the region. Back in
                            2012, she co-founded the Juniper Fund, which provides life insurance and job training for
                            Sherpa people whose family members have died or gotten injured while working on the
                            mountain.
                            “Nepal is so important to me,” she says. “The guiding industry on Everest is relatively
                            young and we can shape it. You see a lot of really negative articles about Everest climbs
                            these days and it’s not quite like that—but it’s still not as good as it could be.”
